1. Use-after-free on the mutex: In the copy constructor and destructor, multiple threads may attempt to lock *mtx after another thread has already decremented the reference count to zero and deleted mtx. Because the mutex lives in the control block and is deleted with it, any concurrent thread still holding a raw pointer to that mutex will access freed memory, causing immediate undefined behavior or crashes.
2. Aliasing self-assignment: In operator=, the guard `if (this != &other)` only checks object identity. If two distinct SharedPtr instances manage the same underlying object, the operator first decrements the shared ref_count (potentially destroying the object, ref_count, and mtx) and then reads from other.ptr / other.mtx, resulting in use-after-free or double-free.
3. Non-atomic reads in copy/assignment: The copy constructor and assignment operator read other.ptr, other.ref_count, and other.mtx without synchronization. If another thread is concurrently assigning to or destroying other, these reads constitute data races and undefined behavior under the C++ memory model.
4. Exception safety leak: In the constructor, if `new std::mutex` throws after `new int(1)` succeeds, the raw pointer p and the allocated int are leaked because no cleanup is performed.
5. Null dereference: operator* and operator-> lack nullptr checks and will crash when called on an empty SharedPtr.
6. Missing move semantics: The absence of a move constructor and move assignment operator causes unnecessary overhead and prevents exception-safe transfers.

